to corrupt. Corrumpo, 3; dēprāvo, 1; vĭtio, 1; perverto, 3 (only corrumpe
for corrupting, bribery).—To corrupt beforehand, præcorrumpo.—For
what is civil law? It is that which cannot be swayed by influence, nor
broken down by power, nor corrupted by bribery. Quid enim est jus
civile? quod neque inflecti gratiâ, neque perfringi potentiâ, neque adulterri
pecuniâ possit. Cic.
corrupt. Corruptus, i. e. debauched. Prăvus, perdĭtus, dissolutus.—Did
you expect that there would be any tribunal at Rome so profligate, so
abandoned, so corrupt? Ecquod judicium Romæ tam dissolutum, tam
perditum, tam nummarium fore putâsti? Cic.
a corrupter. Corruptor, fem. -trix.
corruption. Corruptēla (used especially of seducing into vice). Corruptio,
depravatio; i. e. bribery, largītio.—See bribe.
corruptly. Corrupte, deprăvāte, vĭtōse.
corruptible, i. e. perishable. Cădūcus.

a cover. Tegmen, ĭnis, n. tegŭmen, tegmentum, tegumentum, ŏperculum
(esp. such as a lid), ŏpĕrīmentum. Plin.—Anything wrapped round, invŏ-

hiding-place, lătĕbra, usu. in pl.—Under cover of taking aid to the By
zantines. Per speciem auxilii Byzantinis ferendi. Liv.—See pretence.
to cover. Tĕgo, 3; contego, obtego, intego; ŏpĕrio, 4; cooperio, so as to
hide, q. ., abdo, 3; abscondo.—All those things have crowned me with
undying glory. Mihi illa omnia immortalem gloriam dederunt. Cic.—
Nature has covered the eyes with very thin membranes. Natura oculo
membranis tenuissimis vestivit. Cic.
